Why does ISIS persist?
New York – Lethal terrorist attacks in Istanbul, Dhaka, and Baghdad show that the grip of Islamic State (ISIS) has reached across Europe, North Africa, the Middle East, and Asia.
The longer ISIS maintains its strength in Syria and Iraq, the longer its terrorist network will be capable of staging such massacres.
But ISIS is not particularly difficult to eradicate.
The problem is that the countries involved in Iraq and Syria, including the United States and its allies, have not made ISIS their primary enemy.
This should have changed.
ISIS has a small fighting force, with the U.S. estimating between 20,000 to 25,000 fighters in Iraq and Syria, and around 5,000 in Libya.
In comparison to active military personnel in Syria (125,000), Iraq (271,500), Saudi Arabia (233,500), Turkey (510,600), and Iran (523,000), ISIS is insignificant.
In September 2014, President Obama promised to "degrade and ultimately destroy" ISIS, but the U.S. and its allies, including Saudi Arabia, Turkey, and Israel (in the shadows), have focused on toppling Syrian President Bashar al-Assad.
Recently, General Herzi Halevy of the Israeli Army bluntly stated (as reported by a journalist present at a Halevy speech to me): "Israel does not want to see a scenario where ISIS is defeated, superpowers exit the region, and Israel faces a stronger Hezbollah and Iran."
Israel opposes ISIS, but its greater concern is Iran behind Assad.
Assad allows Iran to support Israel's two main quasi-military opponents — Hezbollah and Hamas.
Therefore, Israel's focus is on toppling Assad, not defeating ISIS.
Influenced by neoconservatism, for the US, the war in Syria is a continuation of the global US hegemony plan proposed by Defense Secretary Dick Cheney and Deputy Secretary of State Paul Wolfowitz at the end of the Cold War.
In 1991, Wolfowitz told US General Wesley Clark:
"But we did learn one thing from the Gulf War — that we could use force in the region — in the Middle East — without the Soviets stopping us.
We had about five to ten years to clean up the old Soviet powers — Syria, Iran, Iraq — before the next superpower came along to challenge us."
The US wars in the Middle East — Afghanistan, Iraq, Syria, Libya, etc. — were to ensure that the Soviets, and subsequently the Russians, exited the competition so that the US could establish its hegemony alone.
These "efforts" have been dismal failures.
For Saudi Arabia, and for Israel, the main objective was to topple Assad to weaken Iran.
<s>Syria is part of a massive proxy war between Shia Iran and Sunni Saudi Arabia, which plays out on battlefields in Syria and Yemen, and at the frontlines of intense Shia-Sunni polarization in divided states such as Bahrain and others in the region, including Saudi Arabia itself.
<s>For Turkey, toppling Assad would strengthen its regional position.
<s>But Turkey now faces three opponents on its southern border: Assad, ISIS, and nationalist Kurds.
<s>So far, ISIS has been less important to Turkey than Assad and the Kurds.
<s>But ISIS-planned terrorist attacks in Turkey could change this situation.
Russia and Iran also pursue their own regional interests through proxy wars and support for quasi-military operations.
However, both countries have expressed readiness to cooperate with the U.S. to combat ISIS, and they can also cooperate on other issues.
So far, the U.S. has remained unmoved because its focus is on overthrowing Assad.
U.S. diplomats criticize Russian President Putin for supporting Assad, while Russia condemns the U.S. for trying to topple Assad.
These complaints appear to be in opposition, but they are not.
<s>U.S. attempts to overthrow Assad violate the UN Charter, while Russia's support for Assad aligns with the Charter's provisions for Syria's right to self-defense.
<s>Indeed, Assad is a dictator, but the UN Charter does not grant any country the power to choose which dictator to overthrow.
<s>The persistence of ISIS highlights three strategic flaws in U.S. foreign policy and one致命战术缺陷.
<s>First, neoconservatism's requirement to achieve American hegemony through regime change is not only a manifestation of bloodthirsty ignorance; it is also a classic case of imperial overreach.
<s>Wherever the U.S. has attempted this, it has always ended in failure.
SYRIA and LIBYA are the latest examples.
Second, the CIA has long funded and trained Sunni jihadis through secret operations in Saudi Arabia.
In turn, these jihadis gave rise to ISIS, a direct (if unintended) consequence of the same policy pursued by the CIA and its Saudi collaborators.
Third, the United States viewing Iran and Russia as irreconcilable enemies to a large extent has become a self-fulfilling outmoded prophecy.
Realigning relations with both countries is possible.
<s>Fourth, at the tactical level, the U.S. attempt to fight a dual war against Assad and ISIS has failed.
<s>Whenever Assad is weakened, Sunni jihadists, including ISIS and the Nusra Front, will fill the vacuum.
<s>If the U.S., Russia, Saudi Arabia, and Iran provide air cover and logistical support, Assad and his Iraqi allies can defeat ISIS.
<s>Of course, Assad will continue to hold power; of course, Russia will remain a ally of Syria; of course, Iran will gain influence there.
<s>Terrorist attacks will certainly continue, perhaps for some time still under the name of ISIS; but the organization will be expelled from its operational bases in Syria and Iraq.
<s>This outcome not only can eliminate ISIS from the lands of the Middle East; it can also lay the groundwork for more comprehensive efforts to ease regional tensions.
<s>The U.S. and Russia could begin to reverse the new Cold War by jointly expelling jihadist terrorism.
<s>(NATO's commitment to not allow Ukraine into the alliance or escalate ballistic missile defense in Eastern Europe would also help.)
<s>There are additional benefits.
<s>Tackling ISIS through cooperation would give Saudi Arabia and Turkey reasons and opportunities to seek new compromises with Iran.
<s>Israel's security could be strengthened by enabling Iran to build cooperative economic and geo-political relationships with the West, thereby increasing the chances of a two-state settlement between Israel and Palestine.
<s>The rise of ISIS is a manifestation of strategic flaws in the current Western approach — especially that of the United States.
<s>Western powers could defeat ISIS.
<s>The question is whether the United States will undertake a strategic reassessment necessary to achieve this goal.
